const SP1 = "Mr Halloran kept his shop exactly as his father had left it: the same brass scales, the same jars of boiled sweets gone cloudy with age, the same hand-lettered sign forbidding credit. Customers were fewer each year, and he knew it, but when the supermarket opened on the corner he only polished his counter a little harder and arrived a little earlier, as though punctuality alone might hold back the tide. He never once spoke of closing. To say the word aloud would have been to admit that the shop, and perhaps he himself, belonged to a world that no longer had any use for them.";
const SP2 = "The letter had sat on the hall table for three days before Eleanor opened it. She told herself she was simply busy, that the garden needed tending and the accounts were behind; but each time she passed the small white envelope she walked a little faster, as one hurries past a window one does not wish to look through. When at last she broke the seal, the words inside were briefer and kinder than she had feared, and she sat for a long while holding them, surprised to find that dread, once met, weighs so much less than dread imagined.";
const SP3 = "Tomas had been warned that the city would change him, and he had laughed at the warning, certain that a person carried his home inside him like a coin sewn into a coat. For the first year he wrote letters describing the strangeness of everything. By the third year the letters had stopped, not because he had forgotten his village but because he no longer found it strange that he had two lives, and could no longer say with confidence which of them was the disguise.";

const PO1 = "The orchard that we planted young\nnow leans its weight against the wall;\nwe meant to pick the fruit ourselves\nbut left it, season after season, to fall.\n\nStill every spring it tries again,\nas if forgetting were a kind of grace,\nand offers to the empty lane\nthe blossom no one comes to face.";
const PO2 = "They built the lighthouse for the ships,\nbut the ships have found another way;\nthe keeper climbs the stair each night\nand lights a lamp for empty bay.\n\nCall it duty, call it pride,\nor the simple need to keep a vow:\nhe turns the great lens to the dark\nand asks of no one why, or how.";
const PO3 = "I thought the river argued with the stone,\nall summer long, in one unbroken word;\nbut autumn showed me, when the banks were bare,\nit was the stone that shaped what I had heard.\nThe water only borrowed, for a while,\nthe stubborn sentence it appeared to say,\nand carried, when I was not listening,\nthe quiet of the stone it wore away.";

const SB1 = "Supporters of the new screen-time limits point to the steep rise in reported anxiety among teenagers over the past decade, a rise that closely tracks the spread of smartphones. Critics, however, note that the same period saw rising academic pressure, falling household incomes in many regions, and a growing willingness to report mental-health concerns that once went unspoken. To read the correlation as proof that screens cause anxiety is to mistake a crowded room for an empty one: the variable we have named may simply be the one we happened to be looking for.";
const SB2 = "It is often claimed that a society can be judged by how it treats its prisoners. The principle is appealing, but it conceals a difficulty. Treatment that one era calls humane, a later era may call cruel, and a third may call indulgent; the standard moves with the values of the judge. Perhaps the more revealing measure is not the comfort a society offers those it has condemned, but the care it takes before condemning them at all.";
const SB3 = "When a policy succeeds, its supporters credit its design; when it fails, they blame its execution. The arrangement is convenient, because it makes the policy itself unfalsifiable: no outcome can ever count against it. A genuine test would require its advocates to state, in advance, what result would persuade them they were wrong. Until they do, what is offered as evidence of success is better understood as an article of faith.";

const GR1 = "A political cartoon shows a large figure labelled 'THE ECONOMY' lying in a hospital bed, hooked to a drip labelled 'STIMULUS'. A doctor labelled 'GOVERNMENT' stands beside the bed, beaming at reporters and pointing to the patient's faint smile, while behind him a second monitor, unwatched, shows a flat line labelled 'WAGES'.";
const GR2 = "A cartoon depicts two people carrying an enormous wrapped gift box together up a steep hill. The box is labelled 'PROGRESS'. The first person, near the top, is dressed in fine clothes and looks back with a wide smile; the second, struggling at the bottom under most of the weight, is in work clothes and cannot see over the box at all.";
const GR3 = "A table titled 'Survey: would you support the new bridge?' shows: Region North - 62% Yes, 38% No (420 surveyed); Region South - 41% Yes, 59% No (1,180 surveyed); a footnote reads 'Surveys conducted outside the proposed northern on-ramp.'";

const HSA = "A photograph, unlike a memory, does not fade; and it is precisely this permanence that makes it treacherous. The remembered face softens and recomposes itself with each recollection, absorbing the moods of the rememberer until it becomes less a record than a companion. The photographed face, by contrast, is fixed at an instant the sitter did not choose and cannot revise. We imagine that the photograph preserves the past, but what it preserves is only a surface, severed from the duration that gave it meaning. To look at an old photograph is therefore to be confronted not with the past itself but with its irrecoverable exterior, and the melancholy peculiar to such images arises from this: they show us everything except the one thing we want, which is the continuance of the moment beyond its own border.";
const HSB = "It is fashionable to insist that, in a democracy, every opinion deserves equal weight. The principle is generous, but it conflates two things that ought to be kept apart: the equal right to hold an opinion and the unequal reliability of opinions once held. A citizen's right to a view on the safety of a bridge is indeed equal to an engineer's; the worth of their views, as guides to whether the bridge will stand, is not. To treat the two as identical is not to honour democracy but to abolish the very notion of expertise, and with it the possibility that some questions have answers at all. The democratic instinct is sound where it concerns ends, the values a society chooses to pursue; it becomes incoherent only when extended to means, the technical questions of how those ends might be reached.";
const HSC = "We speak of progress as though it were a single road leading in one direction, so that to move along it is necessarily to improve. But the metaphor flatters us. A society may grow richer while growing more anxious, more connected while growing lonelier, more capable while growing less wise. Each of these advances is real; none is illusory; yet their sum does not obviously point one way. The error lies in supposing that because we can measure some things, those are the things that matter, and that what eludes measurement may be safely ignored. A civilisation that mistakes its instruments for its purposes will keep its accounts impeccably and lose, without noticing, the very goods the accounts were meant to serve.";
const HSD = "What the Map Omits\n\nThe cartographer, who loved his country, drew\neach river truer than the rivers were,\nand where a marsh had drowned a hopeful road\nhe inked a firm intention through the blur.\n\nHis maps were beautiful. Men set their course\nby confident green meadows that, in fact,\nwere bog; and cursed, waist-deep, the careful hand\nthat drew the world it wished, and called it fact.\n\nYet who would keep the other kind of map,\nall honest swamp, no promise in the lines?\nWe ask of those who chart us, not the truth,\nbut somewhere firm to stand among the signs.";

const GAMSAT_S1_QUESTIONS = [
  { id: "gs1-prose-001", genre: "prose", skill: "characterisation", stimulusId: "gs1-sp1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SP1, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Mr Halloran is portrayed primarily as a man who is...", format: "single_best", options: ["resigned to the changes around him", "bitter towards his dwindling customers", "stubbornly loyal to a fading way of life", "eager to compete with the supermarket"], answer: 2, explanation: "He refuses to speak of closing and responds to the supermarket by clinging harder to his routines, which conveys stubborn loyalty rather than resignation, bitterness or a wish to compete.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-002", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sp1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SP1, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The detail that he 'polished his counter a little harder' when the supermarket opened most strongly suggests that he...", format: "single_best", options: ["met the threat by deepening his routine rather than confronting it", "intended to sell the shop", "had already given up", "hoped to win over the supermarket's customers"], answer: 0, explanation: "Polishing harder is a retreat into familiar habit, implying he copes with the threat by intensifying routine rather than by directly addressing it.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-003", genre: "prose", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-sp1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SP1, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The narrator's attitude towards Mr Halloran is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["mocking", "sympathetic", "indifferent", "alarmed"], answer: 1, explanation: "The narrator presents his stubbornness with understanding and a touch of pathos rather than ridicule or detachment, so the tone is sympathetic.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-004", genre: "prose", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-sp1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SP1, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In context, 'hold back the tide' refers to Mr Halloran's attempt to...", format: "single_best", options: ["raise his prices against inflation", "clean the shop more thoroughly", "manage a flood of new customers", "resist forces largely beyond his control"], answer: 3, explanation: "The tide is a metaphor for the larger economic change overtaking the shop, which his small efforts cannot actually stop.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-005", genre: "prose", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-sp1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SP1, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage is mainly concerned with...", format: "single_best", options: ["the economics of small retail", "one man's quiet refusal to accept that his world has passed", "the rivalry between a shop and a supermarket", "the importance of arriving early to work"], answer: 1, explanation: "The concrete details all serve a larger theme: a man holding on to a way of life that the world no longer needs.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-prose-006", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sp2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SP2, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Eleanor's behaviour before opening the letter suggests that she...", format: "single_best", options: ["had forgotten the letter was there", "was too busy to manage her affairs", "did not care what the letter said", "was avoiding news she expected to be bad"], answer: 3, explanation: "Walking faster past the envelope, like avoiding a window, shows deliberate avoidance of feared news, not forgetfulness or indifference.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-007", genre: "prose", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-sp2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SP2, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The closing sentence most clearly conveys the idea that...", format: "single_best", options: ["anticipated fear is often heavier than the thing feared", "bad news is always exaggerated by others", "Eleanor was wrong to open the letter", "kindness can be found in unexpected places"], answer: 0, explanation: "The contrast between 'dread imagined' and 'dread, once met' states that the imagined fear weighed more than the reality.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-008", genre: "prose", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-sp2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SP2, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The comparison to hurrying 'past a window one does not wish to look through' chiefly emphasises Eleanor's...", format: "single_best", options: ["physical tiredness", "dislike of her home", "wish not to confront something", "curiosity about the letter"], answer: 2, explanation: "The image captures a deliberate refusal to look at, and so confront, something she would rather not face.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-009", genre: "prose", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-sp2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SP2, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "By the end of the passage, the mood has shifted from...", format: "single_best", options: ["anger to forgiveness", "confidence to doubt", "apprehension to relief", "grief to despair"], answer: 2, explanation: "The passage moves from days of dread and avoidance to the surprise of relief when the feared news proves gentler than imagined.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-prose-010", genre: "prose", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-sp3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SP3, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage is primarily about...", format: "single_best", options: ["how migration can quietly divide a person's sense of self", "the hardships of moving to a city", "Tomas's failure to keep in touch with his family", "the superiority of city life over village life"], answer: 0, explanation: "The heart of the passage is Tomas's loss of certainty about which of his two lives is real, a quiet inner division rather than a practical hardship.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-011", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sp3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SP3, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Tomas stopped writing letters mainly because...", format: "single_best", options: ["he had forgotten his village", "the strangeness that had filled the letters had faded", "he resented his family", "he could no longer afford to send them"], answer: 1, explanation: "The passage says the letters stopped not from forgetting but because he no longer found his situation strange, so there was nothing remarkable to report.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-012", genre: "prose", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-sp3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SP3, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The image of 'a coin sewn into a coat' represents Tomas's early belief that...", format: "single_best", options: ["he would become wealthy in the city", "home is a burden one must hide", "he should keep his past hidden from others", "one's origins are carried within, safe and unchanged"], answer: 3, explanation: "The sewn-in coin is a private, portable thing carried inside; it stands for his early conviction that his home self would travel with him intact.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-013", genre: "prose", skill: "characterisation", stimulusId: "gs1-sp3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SP3, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Compared with the Tomas of the first year, the Tomas of the third year is...", format: "single_best", options: ["more homesick", "less sure where he truly belongs", "more certain of who he is", "more eager to return home"], answer: 1, explanation: "By the third year he cannot say which of his two lives is the disguise, so he is markedly less certain of where he belongs.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-014", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sp3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SP3, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The warning that the city 'would change him' is shown by the passage to have been...", format: "single_best", options: ["entirely mistaken", "true only in financial terms", "a deliberate exaggeration", "true, but in a subtler way than a warning usually implies"], answer: 3, explanation: "The change is real but quiet and internal, a shift in his sense of self rather than the obvious transformation a warning might suggest.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-poetry-001", genre: "poetry", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-po1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: PO1, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The poem is chiefly about...", format: "single_best", options: ["something tended in hope but left unharvested", "the difficulty of growing fruit trees", "the beauty of orchards in spring", "a quarrel between neighbours"], answer: 0, explanation: "The orchard was planted with intention but its fruit is left to fall, making neglected hope the central concern.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-002", genre: "poetry", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-po1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: PO1, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The tone of the poem is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["triumphant", "angry", "wistful", "playful"], answer: 2, explanation: "Images of fruit left to fall and blossom no one comes to face create a gentle, regretful, wistful tone.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-003", genre: "poetry", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-po1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: PO1, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "That the orchard 'tries again' each spring 'as if forgetting were a kind of grace' suggests the blossom is...", format: "single_best", options: ["a sign of decay", "a warning to the owners", "an act of generosity offered despite neglect", "evidence the trees are dying"], answer: 2, explanation: "The orchard keeps offering blossom to an empty lane, framed as grace, which presents it as continued generosity in spite of being ignored.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-004", genre: "poetry", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-po1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: PO1, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The phrase 'we meant to pick the fruit ourselves' most strongly implies...", format: "single_best", options: ["a good intention that was never acted upon", "a successful harvest", "a deliberate decision to waste the fruit", "a dislike of the orchard"], answer: 0, explanation: "'Meant to' but 'left it to fall' marks an intention that was formed but never carried out.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-poetry-005", genre: "poetry", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-po2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: PO2, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The poem is mainly a portrait of...", format: "single_best", options: ["the dangers of the sea", "devotion to a duty that may no longer be needed", "the decline of seaside towns", "a keeper's fear of the dark"], answer: 1, explanation: "The ships have gone yet the keeper still lights the lamp nightly for an empty bay, making persistent, possibly needless devotion the focus.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-006", genre: "poetry", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-po2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: PO2, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "That the keeper 'asks of no one why, or how' suggests he...", format: "single_best", options: ["does not understand his job", "hopes the ships will return", "is angry at being abandoned", "continues without requiring his work to be justified"], answer: 3, explanation: "He keeps his vow without demanding a reason, implying his devotion does not depend on the task still being useful.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-007", genre: "poetry", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-po2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: PO2, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The speaker's attitude towards the keeper is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["scornful", "quietly admiring", "pitying and dismissive", "amused"], answer: 1, explanation: "The poem treats the keeper's faithfulness with respect, listing duty, pride and a kept vow, which conveys quiet admiration rather than scorn or pity.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-008", genre: "poetry", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-po2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: PO2, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "In the poem, the lighthouse lamp lit for an 'empty bay' functions as an image of...", format: "single_best", options: ["wasted resources", "the keeper's loneliness alone", "the danger of the coastline", "faithfulness that persists without an audience"], answer: 3, explanation: "Lighting a guiding lamp where no ships come captures devotion that continues even when no one needs or sees it.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-poetry-009", genre: "poetry", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-po3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: PO3, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The central realisation of the poem is that...", format: "single_best", options: ["what seemed to be the river's voice was really shaped by the stone", "rivers are louder in summer than autumn", "stones are stronger than water", "the speaker misheard the river entirely"], answer: 0, explanation: "The speaker learns that the 'sentence' he attributed to the water was actually shaped by the stone it wore away.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-010", genre: "poetry", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-po3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: PO3, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The 'argument' between river and stone is best understood as a metaphor for...", format: "single_best", options: ["a literal sound the speaker enjoys", "the destruction of the landscape", "the way a visible, noisy force can be quietly governed by a hidden, steady one", "the changing of the seasons"], answer: 2, explanation: "The loud water seems to speak, but it is the silent, enduring stone that shapes the sound, dramatising how a hidden steady force can govern a noisy visible one.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-011", genre: "poetry", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-po3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: PO3, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "When the speaker says the water 'only borrowed' its sentence, 'borrowed' implies the sound was...", format: "single_best", options: ["permanently the water's own", "stolen and never returned", "taken temporarily from another source", "invented by the speaker"], answer: 2, explanation: "'Borrowed' marks the sound as temporary and not truly the water's own; it came from, and returns to, the stone.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-012", genre: "poetry", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-po3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: PO3, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The speaker's attitude in the final lines is one of...", format: "single_best", options: ["calm, corrected understanding", "frustration at being deceived", "indifference to the landscape", "pride in being right all along"], answer: 0, explanation: "The speaker accepts the correction quietly, ending on 'the quiet of the stone', which conveys calm, revised understanding rather than frustration.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-sb-001", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-sb1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SB1, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The author's main point is that...", format: "single_best", options: ["screens are the chief cause of teenage anxiety", "a correlation between screens and anxiety does not establish that screens are the cause", "the rise in anxiety is imaginary", "academic pressure is the real cause of anxiety"], answer: 1, explanation: "The author warns against reading correlation as proof of cause and names rival explanations, without endorsing any single cause.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-002", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SB1, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The phrase 'mistake a crowded room for an empty one' is used to suggest that...", format: "single_best", options: ["the data set is too small", "screens are clearly the only factor", "anxiety is not really rising", "other causes are present but overlooked because attention was fixed on screens"], answer: 3, explanation: "The room is crowded with other possible causes; focusing only on screens treats it as if those other factors were not there.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-003", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SB1, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The author would most likely agree that...", format: "single_best", options: ["screen-time limits should be abolished", "we should be cautious about claiming a single cause for a complex trend", "teenagers are not really more anxious than before", "smartphones have no effect on wellbeing"], answer: 1, explanation: "The passage urges caution about causal claims; it neither denies the trend nor rules screens in or out, which is the cautious middle reading the text supports.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-004", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-sb1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SB1, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In the final sentence, 'the one we happened to be looking for' refers to...", format: "single_best", options: ["a cause proven by the data", "a variable chosen at random", "the most important cause", "the cause we were already inclined to find"], answer: 3, explanation: "The author suggests screens may be highlighted simply because that is the explanation observers were already disposed to look for.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-sb-005", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-sb2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SB2, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage chiefly argues that...", format: "single_best", options: ["judging a society by its treatment of prisoners is less reliable than it seems", "prisoners should be treated more comfortably", "every era treats prisoners cruelly", "societies should never condemn anyone"], answer: 0, explanation: "The author questions the familiar maxim, noting the standard shifts with the values of the judge, and proposes a different measure.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-006", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SB2, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The author's main objection to the popular principle is that...", format: "single_best", options: ["prisoners cannot be treated fairly", "societies rarely condemn anyone", "the standard of 'humane treatment' changes depending on the era's values", "comfort is impossible to measure"], answer: 2, explanation: "The difficulty the author identifies is that what counts as humane treatment moves with the values of the judging era, making the test unstable.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-007", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SB2, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The author proposes that a more revealing measure of a society is...", format: "single_best", options: ["how comfortable its prisons are", "how quickly it punishes wrongdoing", "the care it takes before condemning people at all", "how many people it imprisons"], answer: 2, explanation: "The closing sentence offers the care taken before condemning as the more revealing measure.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-008", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-sb2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SB2, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The author's stance towards the popular maxim is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["thoughtful scepticism", "enthusiastic agreement", "outright contempt", "complete indifference"], answer: 0, explanation: "The author finds the maxim 'appealing' but exposes a hidden difficulty and refines it, which is thoughtful scepticism rather than contempt.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-sb-009", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SB3, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The central flaw the author identifies is that the policy's advocates...", format: "single_best", options: ["never measure outcomes at all", "have arranged things so no result could ever count against the policy", "blame the public for failures", "refuse to fund the policy properly"], answer: 1, explanation: "Crediting design for success and execution for failure means no outcome can disprove the policy, which the author calls unfalsifiable.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-010", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-sb3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SB3, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "By calling the claimed success 'an article of faith', the author means it is...", format: "single_best", options: ["supported by strong evidence", "a temporary opinion", "a religious belief", "held regardless of evidence"], answer: 3, explanation: "An article of faith is believed independently of evidence, which is the author's charge against the unfalsifiable claim of success.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-011", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SB3, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The author implies that a genuine test of the policy would require advocates to...", format: "single_best", options: ["spend more money on it", "say in advance what result would show them to be wrong", "consult the public first", "wait longer before judging"], answer: 1, explanation: "The author states a genuine test needs advocates to specify in advance what outcome would persuade them they were wrong.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-012", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-sb3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SB3, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage is best summarised as an argument for...", format: "single_best", options: ["abandoning all government policy", "the success of the policy in question", "trusting experts over the public", "judging claims by whether they could in principle be proven wrong"], answer: 3, explanation: "The whole passage turns on falsifiability: a claim that no outcome could disprove is treated as faith, not evidence.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-graphic-001", genre: "graphic", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-gr1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: GR1, attribution: "Described cartoon (original)" }, stem: "The cartoon's main point is that the government is...", format: "single_best", options: ["celebrating a superficial recovery while ignoring a deeper problem", "successfully curing the economy", "harming the economy on purpose", "uninterested in the economy"], answer: 0, explanation: "The beaming doctor points at a faint smile and the stimulus drip while the unwatched 'WAGES' monitor flatlines, mocking a shallow recovery that ignores the deeper issue.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-002", genre: "graphic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-gr1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: GR1, attribution: "Described cartoon (original)" }, stem: "The unwatched 'WAGES' monitor showing a flat line is included to suggest that...", format: "single_best", options: ["wages are rising quickly", "the patient has fully recovered", "a serious problem is being overlooked amid the celebration", "wages are not part of the economy"], answer: 2, explanation: "A flatline normally signals crisis; placing it unwatched behind the celebration implies a grave problem is being ignored.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-003", genre: "graphic", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-gr1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: GR1, attribution: "Described cartoon (original)" }, stem: "The cartoonist's attitude towards the government is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["admiring", "neutral", "satirical", "fearful"], answer: 2, explanation: "Exaggerating the doctor's self-congratulation while a crisis goes unnoticed is a satirical criticism, not admiration or neutrality.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-graphic-004", genre: "graphic", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-gr2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: GR2, attribution: "Described cartoon (original)" }, stem: "The cartoon most strongly suggests that 'progress' is...", format: "single_best", options: ["enjoyed by some while its costs fall on others", "shared equally by everyone", "impossible to achieve", "disliked by the well-dressed figure"], answer: 0, explanation: "The well-dressed figure near the top smiles while the worker at the bottom bears most of the weight and cannot even see ahead, implying unequal costs and benefits.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-005", genre: "graphic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-gr2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: GR2, attribution: "Described cartoon (original)" }, stem: "That the lower figure 'cannot see over the box at all' implies that this person...", format: "single_best", options: ["benefits most from progress", "bears the burden without a clear view of where it leads", "is taller than the other figure", "refuses to help carry the box"], answer: 1, explanation: "Carrying most of the weight yet unable to see ahead suggests the worker bears the cost of progress without sharing in its vision or direction.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-006", genre: "graphic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-gr2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: GR2, attribution: "Described cartoon (original)" }, stem: "Which message does the cartoon most support?", format: "single_best", options: ["Progress requires teamwork between equals", "Fine clothes make work easier", "Progress always reaches the top of the hill", "The rewards and burdens of progress are unevenly distributed"], answer: 3, explanation: "The contrast in dress, position and load points to an uneven distribution of progress's rewards and burdens.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-graphic-007", genre: "graphic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-gr3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: GR3, attribution: "Original data table" }, stem: "Why does the footnote about where the surveys were conducted matter?", format: "single_best", options: ["It proves the bridge will be built", "It suggests the northern result may be biased towards people who benefit from the bridge", "It shows the southern sample was too small", "It confirms both regions agree"], answer: 1, explanation: "Surveying outside the proposed on-ramp would oversample those most likely to gain from the bridge, casting doubt on the northern 'Yes' figure.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-008", genre: "graphic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-gr3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: GR3, attribution: "Original data table" }, stem: "Considering both the percentages and the sample sizes, the data most strongly indicate that...", format: "single_best", options: ["overall support is clearly in favour", "support is identical in both regions", "the two regions surveyed equal numbers of people", "far more of those surveyed opposed the bridge than supported it"], answer: 3, explanation: "The South had a much larger sample (1,180) with 59% opposed, so across both regions many more respondents opposed than supported the bridge.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-009", genre: "graphic", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-gr3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: GR3, attribution: "Original data table" }, stem: "The table is best used as a caution that...", format: "single_best", options: ["headline percentages can mislead unless sample size and method are considered", "surveys are always wrong", "the North is more reliable than the South", "bridges are unpopular everywhere"], answer: 0, explanation: "The differing sample sizes and the location footnote show why raw percentages alone can mislead without attention to method and scale.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-poetry-013", genre: "poetry", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-po3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: PO3, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The phrase 'when I was not listening' most strongly implies that the deeper truth...", format: "single_best", options: ["was announced loudly to the speaker", "was explained by someone else", "emerged only once the speaker stopped attending to the obvious sound", "was never really discovered"], answer: 2, explanation: "The stone's quiet work is carried out unnoticed; the truth surfaces only when the speaker is no longer fixed on the river's obvious noise.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-010", genre: "graphic", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-gr1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: GR1, attribution: "Described cartoon (original)" }, stem: "The drip labelled 'STIMULUS' keeping the patient alive chiefly implies that the recovery is...", format: "single_best", options: ["natural and self-sustaining", "already complete", "dependent on artificial support rather than underlying health", "no longer necessary"], answer: 2, explanation: "A patient kept going by a drip is sustained from outside; the image suggests the recovery rests on artificial support, not genuine health.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-013", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-sb1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SB1, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The author's tone throughout the passage is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["measured and analytical", "alarmed and partisan", "mocking and dismissive", "confused and uncertain"], answer: 0, explanation: "The author weighs competing explanations carefully and warns against hasty conclusions, a measured, analytical tone rather than an alarmed or mocking one.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-hard-001", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-hsa", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HSA, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage suggests that the 'treachery' of a photograph lies in...", format: "single_best", options: ["its tendency to fade over time", "its fixing of a single surface, cut off from the lived duration that gave it meaning", "the sitter's inability to choose the instant captured", "the unreliability of the rememberer's shifting moods"], answer: 1, explanation: "The photograph's very permanence fixes only a surface, severed from the duration that gave the moment meaning; that, the passage says, is what makes it treacherous, in contrast to the fluid, recomposing memory.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-hard-002", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-hsa", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HSA, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "According to the passage, a remembered face differs from a photographed face chiefly in that the remembered face...", format: "single_best", options: ["is a more accurate historical record", "is fixed at an instant the subject did not choose", "changes and recomposes itself over time", "preserves the duration of the original moment"], answer: 2, explanation: "The remembered face 'softens and recomposes itself with each recollection', whereas the photograph is fixed. Option D inverts the passage, which denies that the photograph preserves duration.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-hard-003", genre: "prose", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-hsa", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HSA, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which statement is closest to the writer's view of old photographs?", format: "single_best", options: ["They faithfully preserve the past", "They are melancholy because they present a surface while withholding the moment's continuance", "They are more reliable than memory as records", "They are companions that absorb our changing moods"], answer: 1, explanation: "The closing sentence locates the peculiar melancholy of old photographs in their showing 'everything except' the one thing wanted: the continuance of the moment beyond its border.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-hard-004", genre: "prose", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-hsa", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HSA, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In the final sentence, 'its own border' most nearly refers to...", format: "single_best", options: ["the physical edge of the printed photograph", "the temporal limit of the instant the photograph captures", "the frame the sitter chose to pose within", "the boundary between memory and record"], answer: 1, explanation: "The wanted thing is 'the continuance of the moment beyond its own border', which is a matter of time: the border is the edge of the captured instant, not the paper's edge.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-hard-005", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-hsb", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HSB, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The central distinction the passage draws is between...", format: "single_best", options: ["engineers and ordinary citizens", "the equal right to hold an opinion and the unequal reliability of opinions", "democracy and expertise as rival systems", "questions that have answers and questions that do not"], answer: 1, explanation: "The passage separates the equal right to hold a view from the unequal worth of views as guides to truth; that distinction is the hinge of the whole argument.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-hard-006", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-hsb", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HSB, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "On the writer's view, the claim that 'every opinion deserves equal weight' is defensible when it concerns...", format: "single_best", options: ["technical questions of how to reach a goal", "the values or ends a society chooses to pursue", "the structural safety of a bridge", "every question without exception"], answer: 1, explanation: "The writer holds that the democratic instinct is sound for ends (the values pursued) but incoherent when extended to means (technical questions of how).", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-hard-007", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-hsb", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HSB, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which of the following, if true, would most weaken the writer's argument?", format: "single_best", options: ["Equally qualified engineers frequently disagree about whether a given bridge will stand", "Most citizens defer to engineers on technical matters", "Societies should value their ends above their means", "Democracies usually reach good decisions in the end"], answer: 0, explanation: "The argument rests on expert views being more reliable on technical questions. If equally qualified experts routinely disagree, that reliability, and the means/ends distinction built on it, is undermined.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-hard-008", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-hsb", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HSB, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In context, 'conflates' most nearly means...", format: "single_best", options: ["distinguishes with care", "wrongly runs together as one", "weighs against each other", "openly rejects"], answer: 1, explanation: "The passage objects that the principle treats as identical two things 'that ought to be kept apart', that is, it wrongly runs them together.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-hard-009", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-hsc", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HSC, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage is principally a warning against...", format: "single_best", options: ["the pursuit of material wealth", "treating progress as a single beneficial direction and mistaking the measurable for the important", "technological advancement of any kind", "the practice of keeping careful accounts"], answer: 1, explanation: "The passage attacks both the one-directional metaphor of progress and the assumption that only what can be measured matters.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-hard-010", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-hsc", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HSC, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The phrase 'mistakes its instruments for its purposes' implies that a society may...", format: "single_best", options: ["lack the tools needed to measure what matters", "come to prize what it can measure over the ends those measures were meant to serve", "keep deliberately inaccurate accounts", "grow richer without growing more anxious"], answer: 1, explanation: "Instruments are the means of measurement; mistaking them for purposes means valuing the measure itself over the end it was only meant to track.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-hard-011", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-hsc", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HSC, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The writer's attitude towards 'progress' is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["wholly dismissive of any improvement", "uncritically enthusiastic", "sceptical of its simple, one-directional sense", "entirely indifferent"], answer: 2, explanation: "The writer grants that the advances are 'real' and 'not illusory' yet doubts their sum points one way, a sceptical stance rather than a dismissive or indifferent one.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-hard-012", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-hsc", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HSC, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which situation best illustrates the passage's central warning?", format: "single_best", options: ["A school that raises its examination scores while its students grow more fearful of failure", "A school that improves both its scores and its students' wellbeing", "A school that cannot afford to measure its results at all", "A school that ignores examination scores entirely"], answer: 0, explanation: "A measurable good (the score) rises while an unmeasured good (wellbeing) is quietly lost, which is exactly the error of mistaking instruments for purposes.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-hard-013", genre: "poetry", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-hsd", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HSD, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The poem uses the cartographer chiefly as a figure for...", format: "single_best", options: ["the technical difficulty of drawing accurate maps", "those who give us reassuring but misleading accounts of the world because we prefer them", "the beauty that careful craftsmanship can achieve", "the physical dangers of travelling through marshland"], answer: 1, explanation: "The cartographer draws 'the world it wished' and people set their course by it; the final stanza confirms we ask such comforting falsification of those who chart us.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-hard-014", genre: "poetry", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-hsd", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HSD, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The final stanza suggests that people want from 'those who chart us'...", format: "single_best", options: ["complete and honest truth above all else", "beautiful maps regardless of their usefulness", "reassurance and a firm footing, even at the cost of accuracy", "no guidance of any kind"], answer: 2, explanation: "The closing lines say we ask 'not the truth, but somewhere firm to stand among the signs', that is, reassurance preferred over accuracy.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-hard-015", genre: "poetry", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-hsd", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HSD, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The speaker's attitude towards the cartographer is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["purely condemnatory", "admiring without reservation", "critical, yet understanding of the human need he serves", "wholly indifferent"], answer: 2, explanation: "The maps mislead and are cursed, yet the final stanza concedes why people want them, so the speaker is critical but sympathetic to the need.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-hard-016", genre: "poetry", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-hsd", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HSD, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The phrase 'all honest swamp, no promise in the lines' describes a map that...", format: "single_best", options: ["has been carelessly drawn", "shows the world truthfully but offers no reassurance", "depicts nothing but swamps", "contains no rivers at all"], answer: 1, explanation: "It is 'the other kind of map', honest about the bog and therefore offering no comforting promise, set against the cartographer's flattering one.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" }
];

if (typeof window !== "undefined") {
  window.GAMSAT_S1_GENRES = GAMSAT_S1_GENRES;
  window.GAMSAT_S1_SKILLS = GAMSAT_S1_SKILLS;
  window.GAMSAT_S1_TAXONOMY = GAMSAT_S1_TAXONOMY;
  window.GAMSAT_S1_DIFFICULTIES = GAMSAT_S1_DIFFICULTIES;
  window.GAMSAT_S1_QUESTIONS = GAMSAT_S1_QUESTIONS;
}
